an|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image = \n| name = Andrei Churin\n| fullname = Andrei Vyacheslavovich Churin\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|8|2|df=yes}}\n| height = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[FC Volga Nizhny Novgorod]]\n| years1 = 2012\u20132015 | clubs1 = [[FC Volga Nizhny Novgorod]] | caps1 = 18 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2017      | clubs2 = [[FC Zorky Krasnogorsk]]     | caps2 =  1 | goals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 31 August 2017\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n'''Andrei Vyacheslavovich Churin''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0412\u044f\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0427\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043d}}; born 2 August 1995) is a [[Russia]]n [[association football|football]] player.\n\n==Club career==\nHe made his professional debut in the [[Russian Football National League]] for [[FC Volga Nizhny Novgorod]] on 10 August 2014 in a game against [[FC Volgar Astrakhan]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian National Football League]]|url=http://www.1fnl.ru/players/2245/|title=Career Summary|date=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|andrey-churin/347895}}\n* {{FootballFacts.ru|120247-churin-andrej-vyacheslavovich}}\n* [http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Andrey-Vyacheslavovich-CHurin-Futbol-02081995/turnir_10536 Career summary by sportbox.ru]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Churin, Andrei}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:FC Volga Nizhny Novgorod players]]\n\n{{Russia-footy-midfielder-1995-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update FootballFacts.ru template, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrei_Churin"}
{"title_page": "Faqir Ipi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ghazi Mirzali Khan Wazir<br />Faqir Ipi<br />{{lang|ps|\u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a \u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0644\u064a\u200c\u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631<br>\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u064a\u067e\u064a}}\n| other_names = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1897\n| birth_place = Kirta Khajuri, [[Mir Ali Subdivision|Mir Ali]], [[North Waziristan]], [[British India]] (in modern-day [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1960|4|16|1897}}\n| death_place = [[Gurwek]], North Waziristan, [[Pakistan]]\n| resting_place = Gurwek, North Waziristan, Pakistan\n| known_for   = [[Pashtun nationalism]]<br />[[Pashtunistan]] movement<br />[[Indian independence movement]]\n| children    =  \n| parents     = Sheikh Arsala Khan\n| spouse      = \n}}\n'''Ghazi Mirzali Khan Wazir''' ({{lang-ps|\u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a \u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0644\u064a\u200c\u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631}}; b. 1897, d. 16 April 1960), commonly known as '''[[Fakir|Faqir]] Ipi''' ({{lang|ps|\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u064a\u067e\u064a}}), was a [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] tribal leader from [[Waziristan]] in today's [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y20MTE0C9kwC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=mirza+ali+khan+militant&source=bl&ots=2b-lggmgTF&sig=zpY8TajgZzhUlk6okOjlgM18C1I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjA_4zKq8zeAhVMxxoKHXhfAoMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=snippet&q=mirza%20ali%20khan%20militant&f=false|title=A Brief History of Afghanistan|date=2007 |author=Shaista Wahab and Barry Youngerman|publisher=Infobase publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1362485/How-British-empire-failed-to-tame-the-terrorist-Fakir-of-Ipi.html|title=How British empire failed to tame the terrorist Fakir of Ipi|accessdate=15 November 2001|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> After performing his [[Hajj]] pilgrimage in 1923, Mirzali Khan settled in Ipi, a village located near [[Mir Ali, Pakistan|Mir Ali]] in [[North Waziristan]], from where he started his campaign of guerrilla warfare against the [[British Empire]]. In 1938, he shifted from Ipi to [[Gurwek]], a remote village in North Waziristan on the border with [[Afghanistan]], where he declared an independent state and continued the raids against the British Empire, using bases in Afghanistan,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6WYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT157&dq=faqir+of+ipi+jihad&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZq9bwxsTZAhVExmMKHUQAA_IQ6AEIMDAC#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20jihad&f=false|title=Savage Border: The Story of the North-West Frontier|last=Stewart|first=Jules|date=2007-02-22|publisher=The History Press|isbn=9780752496078|language=en}}</ref> with the support of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zUiYBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA387&dq=faqir+of+ipi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi29dbQw8TZAhUELmMKHWIgBHgQ6AEINTAE#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi&f=false|title=Islam and Nazi Germany's War|last=Motadel|first=David|date=2014-11-30|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674724600|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QqLyDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT217&dq=faqir+of+ipi+nazi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2yoOzxcTZAhVT0WMKHSneB6UQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20nazi&f=false|title=Silver: The Spy Who Fooled the Nazis: The Most Remarkable Agent of the Second World War|last=Bose|first=Mihir|date=2017-01-20|publisher=Fonthill Media|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 1947, Faqir Ipi, along with his allies including the [[Khudai Khidmatgars]] and members of the Provincial Assembly, declared the [[Bannu Resolution]]. The resolution demanded that the Pashtuns be given a third choice to have an independent state of [[Pashtunistan]], composing all Pashtun majority territories of British India, instead of being made to join only either India or Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|website=The Nation|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> The [[British Raj]], however, refused to comply with the demand of this resolution,<ref>{{cite book |last=Ali Shah |first=Sayyid Vaqar |date=1993 |title=Afghanistan and the Frontier |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c05uAAAAMAAJ |location=[[University of Michigan]] |publisher=Emjay Books International |page=256 |isbn= |editor1-first=Fazal-ur-Rahim Khan |editor1-last=Marwat}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=H Johnson |first1=Thomas |author-link1=Thomas Howard Johnson |last2=Zellen |first2=Barry |date=2014 |title=Culture, Conflict, and Counterinsurgency |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ZZAgAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |page=154 |isbn= 9780804789219}}</ref> and no other group in British India was granted a third option. After the creation of Pakistan in August 1947, Afghanistan  and India financially sponsored the Pashtunistan movement under the leadership of Faqir Ipi.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yca-DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&dq=faqir+of+ipi+pakistan+afghanistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2j7bfx8TZAhVW9mMKHYtuBfoQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20pakistan%20afghanistan&f=false|title=Soviet-Pakistan Relations and Post-Soviet Dynamics, 1947\u201392|last=Malik|first=Hafeez|date=2016-07-27|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349105731|language=en}}</ref> He continued the guerilla warfare against the new nation\u2019s government.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/77388/the-faqir-of-ipi-of-north-waziristan/ The Faqir of Ipi of North Waziristan]. ''[[The Express Tribune]]''. November 15, 2010.</ref> He didn't surrender to the government of Pakistan and died a natural death in 1960 in Gurwek.<ref name=\"115th anniversary\">[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1086737/april-1891-1960-the-legendary-guerilla-faqir-of-ipi-unremembered-on-his-115th-anniversary/ The legendary guerilla Faqir of Ipi unremembered on his 115th anniversary]. ''The Express Tribune''. April 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMirzali Khan was born in 1897 at Shankai Kirta, a village near Khajuri in the [[Tochi Valley]] of [[North Waziristan]], present day [[Pakistan]] to Sheikh Arsala Khan Wazir.<ref name=\"Alan Warren\">{{cite book|title=Waziristan, the Faqir of Ipi, and the Indian Army: The North West Frontier Revolt of 1936-37|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195790160|page=84|author=Alan Warren}}</ref> He belonged to the Torikhel branch of the [[Utmanzai (Wazir clan)|Utmanzai Wazir]] tribe.<ref name=\"Rob Johnson\">{{cite book|title=The Afghan Way of War: How and Why They Fight|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-979856-8|page=195|author=Rob Johnson}}</ref> His father died when he was twelve. He studied till fourth grade at a government school and later pursued religious studies at [[Bannu]]. He built a mosque and a house at Spalga, further south in North Waziristan agency in 1922. He went to perform [[Hajj]] at [[Mecca]] and later moved to Ipi in mid 1920s. He became a religious figure among the locals and was called \"Haji Sahab\".\n\n== Restoration of King Amanullah Khan ==\nIn 1933, Faqir Ipi went to [[Afghanistan]] to fight against the [[Mohammadzai]] Afghan King at [[Khost]] to support the restoration of King [[Amanullah Khan]]. In 1944, Faqir Ipi joined his fellow [[Loya Paktia]] tribesmen again to support the restoration of Amanullah Khan in the [[Afghan tribal revolts of 1944\u20131947]].<ref name=\"GeorgeHill2013\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TzRlAgAAQBAJ|title=Proceed to Peshawar: The Story of a U.S. Navy Intelligence Mission on the Afghan Border, 1943|last=Hill|first=George|date=2013-11-15|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=|isbn=9781612513287|location=|pages=|quote=Engert letter to State Department, 15 July 1944, says that the rebel leader Abdurrahman, was next in importance to the faqir of Ipi.|language=en|chapter=Chapter 3, the trip (Bibliography near end of the book)}}</ref> Until his death, Faqir Ipi remained involved in Afghan politics as he did not recognize Pakistan.<ref name=\"115th anniversary\">[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1086737/april-1891-1960-the-legendary-guerilla-faqir-of-ipi-unremembered-on-his-115th-anniversary/ The legendary guerilla Faqir of Ipi unremembered on his 115th anniversary]. ''The Express Tribune''. April 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Ram Kori case ==\nIn March 1936, a British Indian court ruled against the marriage of Ram Kori (n\u00e9e Islam Bibi), a Hindu-converted Muslim girl at [[Jhando Khel]], [[Bannu]], after the girl's family filed case of abduction and forced conversion. The ruling was based on the fact that the girl was a minor and was asked to make her decision of conversion and marriage after she reaches the age of majority, till then she was asked to live with a third party.<ref name=\"Yousef Aboul-Enein\">{{cite book|title=The Secret War for the Middle East|year=2013|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1612513096|page=153|author=Yousef Aboul-Enein|author2=Basil Aboul-Enein}}</ref> The verdict enraged the Pashtuns, and further mobilized Faqir Ipi for a guerrilla war against the British Empire. The [[Dawar (Pashtun tribe)|Dawar]] Maliks and mullahs left the Tochi for the Khaisor Valley to the south to rouse the Torikhel [[Wazir (Pashtun tribe)|Wazirs]]. A month after the incident, Faqir Ipi called a tribal [[jirga]] in the village of Ipi near Mir Ali to declare war against the British imperialists.\n\n== Freedom movement against the British Raj ==\nFaqir's decision to declare war against the British was endorsed by the local Pashtun tribes, who mustered two large lashkars 10,000 strong to battle the British. Interestingly, many Pashtun women also took part in the freedom movement, who not only actively participated in the war but also sung ''landai'' (a short folk-song sung by Pashtun women) to inspire the Pashtun fighters. Widespread lawlessness erupted as the Pashtuns blocked roads, overran outposts and ambushed convoys. In November 1936, the British sent two columns to the Khaisor river valley to crush the freedom movement, but suffered heavy casualties.<ref name=\"at\">{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/__trashed-50/|title=Remembering the Faqir of Ipi|website=Asia Times|date=April 16, 2020|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the Khaisor campaign a general uprising broke out throughout [[Waziristan campaign (1936\u20131939)|Waziristan campaign]], realising the futility of confronting the British Army directly especially with their advantage of air power, tribesmen switched to guerrilla warfare. Squadrons of the two air forces ([[RAF]] and RIAF) tried many tactics including scorched earth retaliation involving the burning of standing crops with jerry can petrol bombs and the killing of cattle with strafing attacks.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nIn 1937, the British sent over 40,000 British-Indian troops, mostly [[Sikhs]] from the [[Punjab]], to crush the freedom movement in Waziristan. This was in response to an ambush by Waziristani tribesmen in which they had killed over 50 British soldiers. However, the British operation failed and by December\u060c the troops were sent back to cantonments. In 1939, the British claimed that the war capacity of Faqir Ipi's forces was enhanced by support from [[Nazi Germany]] and [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Italy]], alleging that the Italian diplomat Pietro Quaroni drove the Italian policy for involvement in Waziristan, although the British could not find any valid evidence for Pietro Quaroni's involvement.<ref name=\"at\"/>\n\nThe British suppressed the agitation by imposing fines and by destroying the houses of their leaders, including that of Faqir Ipi. However, the pyrrhic nature of the victory and the subsequent withdrawal of the troops was credited by the Wazirs to be a manifestation of Faqir Ipi's miraculous powers. He succeeded in inducing a semblance of tribal unity, as the British noticed with dismay, among various sections of Wazirs, Dawar, [[Mahsud]]s and [[Bettani]]s. He cemented his position as religious leader by declaring a Jihad against the British. This move also helped rally support from Pashtun tribesman across the border. In 1946, the British again attempted to crush Faqir Ipi's movement but failed.\n\n==Jirga in Bannu==\nOn 21 June 1947, Faqir Ipi, [[Abdul Ghaffar Khan]], and other [[Khudai Khidmatgar]]s held a jirga in Bannu during which they declared the [[Bannu Resolution]], demanding that the Pashtuns be given a choice to have an independent state of [[Pashtunistan]] composing all Pashtun majority territories of British India, instead of being made to join the new dominions of India or Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|website=The Nation|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> However, the British Raj refused to comply with the demand of the Bannu Resolution and only the options for Pakistan and India were given.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ali Shah |first=Sayyid Vaqar |date=1993 |title=Afghanistan and the Frontier |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c05uAAAAMAAJ |location=[[University of Michigan]] |publisher=Emjay Books International |page=256 |isbn= |editor1-first=Fazal-ur-Rahim Khan |editor1-last=Marwat}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=H Johnson |first1=Thomas |author-link1=Thomas Howard Johnson |last2=Zellen |first2=Barry |date=2014 |title=Culture, Conflict, and Counterinsurgency |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ZZAgAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |page=154 |isbn= 9780804789219}}</ref> In response, Faqir Ipi and the Khudai Khidmatgars boycotted the [[1947 North-West Frontier Province referendum]] on joining India or Pakistan, citing that it did not have the options for the province to become independent or join Afghanistan.\n\n== Pashtunistan movement ==\nFaqir Ipi rejected the creation of Pakistan after the [[partition of India]], considering Pakistan to be a continuation of British imperialism. In 1948, Faqir Ipi took control of North Waziristan's [[Datta Khel Subdivision|Datta Khel]] area and declared the establishment of an independent [[Pashtunistan]], forming ties with regional leaders including [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] and Prince [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]]. On 29 May 1949, Faqir Ipi called a tribal jirga in his headquarters of Gurwek and asked Pakistan to accept Pashtunistan as an independent state. He published a Pashto-language newspaper, ''Gh\u0101z\u012b'', from Gurwek to promote his ideas. In January 1950, a Pashtun [[loya jirga]] in [[Razmak]] symbolically appointed Faqir Ipi as the first president of the \"National Assembly for Pashtunistan\". In 1953-54, the [[Pakistan Air Force]] led an operation from Miramshah airbase and heavily bombarded Faqir Ipi's compound in Gurwek.<ref name=\"at\"/> Although he himself never surrendered to Pakistan until his death in 1960 but his movement diminished after 1954 when his [[Commander-in-chief]] Mehar Dil Khan Mehsud surrendered to the [[Pakistani authorities]] and became loyal to the state of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|date=2019-08-24|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nFaqir Ipi died at night on April 16, 1960. A long term sufferer of asthma during his last days, he became so sick that it was not possible for him to walk for a few steps. People from far away often used to come and see him and ask for his blessing.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} His funeral prayers or Namaz-I-Janaza was held at [[Gurwek]] led by Maulavi Pir Rehman. Thousands of people came for his Namaz-I-Janaza.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} He was buried at Gurwek.\n\n[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Faqir+Aipee+Road,+Islamabad,+Islamabad+Capital+Territory,+Pakistan/@33.648256,73.0152781,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x38df95c0bb738de1:0xf02524d4e38fa35e!8m2!3d33.648256!4d73.0174668 Faqir Aipee Road], a main artery connecting I.J.P. Road to the Kashmir Highway in the federal capital of Pakistan, Islamabad; is named after him.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Waziristan]]\n* [[Mulla Powinda]]\n* [[Sartor Faqir]]\n* [[Umra Khan]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Dr. Shah, Syed Wiqar Ali German Activities in the North-West Frontier Province War Years 1914-1945. Quaid-e-Azam University. Available online at [https://web.archive.org/web/20050120221931/http://www.brain.com.pk/~charsadda/articles/germanarticle.htm]. Last accessed on 22/03/06\n* Government of Pakistan: The Frontier Corps (NWFP) Pakistan and its headquarters. Available online at [https://web.archive.org/web/20060405170741/http://www.pak.gov.pk/public/govt/reports/frontier_corps.htm] Last accessed on 22/03/06\n* Siddiqui A. R. Faqir of Ipi's Cross Border Nexus. Available online [https://web.archive.org/web/20060927155808/http://www.khyber.org/people/sarfaroshan/FaqirofIpisCrossBorderNexus.shtml]. Last accessed on 22/03/06.\n* Hauner, Milan (Jan., 1981) One Man against the Empire: The Faqir of Ipi and the British in Central Asia on the Eve of and during the Second World War. Available online at [http://www.khyber.org/publications/021-025/faqiripi.shtml]. Last accessed on 22/03/06.\n* Shah, Idries, Destination Mecca, Chapter XXIII Contains interview with and the only photograph ever taken of Fakir of Ipi (London 1957). Possibly confirms the Fakir's dervish or Sufi status.\n* Batl-i-Hurriyet: Fakir of Ipi\u2014Iman-Parwar Jihad By Dr Fazal-ur-Rehman Kitab Saraay, First Floor, Alhamd Market, Ghazni Street, Urdu Bazar, Lahore\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Waziristan}}\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/waziristan_and_mughal_empire.shtml Waziristan and Mughal empire]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/nehru_in_waziristan.shtml Nehru in Waziristan]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/images/maps/waziristan.gif Sketch map of Waziristan]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/mehsuds_and_wazirs_the_king-ma.shtml Mehsuds and Wazirs, the King-makers in a game of thrones]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/lawrence_of_arabia_in_wazirist.shtml Lawrence of Arabia in Waziristan]\n{{Pashtun nationalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faqir Of Ipi}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from North Waziristan]]\n[[Category:Pashtun people]]\n[[Category:Pashtun nationalists]]\n[[Category:Pashtun Sufis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ghazi Mirzali Khan Wazir<br />Faqir Ipi<br />{{lang|ps|\u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a \u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0644\u064a\u200c\u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631<br>\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u064a\u067e\u064a}}\n| other_names = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1897\n| birth_place = Kirta Khajuri, [[Mir Ali Subdivision|Mir Ali]], [[North Waziristan]], [[British India]] (in modern-day [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1960|4|16|1897}}\n| death_place = [[Gurwek]], North Waziristan, [[Pakistan]]\n| resting_place = Gurwek, North Waziristan, Pakistan\n| known_for   = [[Pashtun nationalism]]<br />[[Pashtunistan]] movement<br />[[Indian independence movement]]\n| children    =  \n| parents     = Sheikh Arsala Khan\n| spouse      = \n}}\n'''Ghazi Mirzali Khan Wazir''' ({{lang-ps|\u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a \u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0644\u064a\u200c\u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631}}; b. 1897, d. 16 April 1960), commonly known as '''[[Fakir|Faqir]] Ipi''' ({{lang|ps|\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u064a\u067e\u064a}}), was a [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] tribal leader from [[Waziristan]] in today's [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y20MTE0C9kwC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=mirza+ali+khan+militant&source=bl&ots=2b-lggmgTF&sig=zpY8TajgZzhUlk6okOjlgM18C1I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjA_4zKq8zeAhVMxxoKHXhfAoMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=snippet&q=mirza%20ali%20khan%20militant&f=false|title=A Brief History of Afghanistan|date=2007 |author=Shaista Wahab and Barry Youngerman|publisher=Infobase publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1362485/How-British-empire-failed-to-tame-the-terrorist-Fakir-of-Ipi.html|title=How British empire failed to tame the terrorist Fakir of Ipi|accessdate=15 November 2001|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> After performing his [[Hajj]] pilgrimage in 1923, Mirzali Khan settled in Ipi, a village located near [[Mir Ali, Pakistan|Mir Ali]] in [[North Waziristan]], from where he started his campaign of guerrilla warfare against the [[British Empire]]. In 1938, he shifted from Ipi to [[Gurwek]], a remote village in North Waziristan on the border with [[Afghanistan]], where he declared an independent state and continued the raids against the British Empire, using bases in Afghanistan,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6WYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT157&dq=faqir+of+ipi+jihad&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZq9bwxsTZAhVExmMKHUQAA_IQ6AEIMDAC#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20jihad&f=false|title=Savage Border: The Story of the North-West Frontier|last=Stewart|first=Jules|date=2007-02-22|publisher=The History Press|isbn=9780752496078|language=en}}</ref> with the support of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zUiYBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA387&dq=faqir+of+ipi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi29dbQw8TZAhUELmMKHWIgBHgQ6AEINTAE#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi&f=false|title=Islam and Nazi Germany's War|last=Motadel|first=David|date=2014-11-30|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674724600|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QqLyDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT217&dq=faqir+of+ipi+nazi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2yoOzxcTZAhVT0WMKHSneB6UQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20nazi&f=false|title=Silver: The Spy Who Fooled the Nazis: The Most Remarkable Agent of the Second World War|last=Bose|first=Mihir|date=2017-01-20|publisher=Fonthill Media|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 1947, Faqir Ipi, along with his allies including the [[Khudai Khidmatgars]] and members of the Provincial Assembly, declared the [[Bannu Resolution]]. The resolution demanded that the Pashtuns be given a third choice to have an independent state of [[Pashtunistan]], composing all Pashtun majority territories of British India, instead of being made to join only either India or Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|website=The Nation|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> The [[British Raj]], however, refused to comply with the demand of this resolution,<ref>{{cite book |last=Ali Shah |first=Sayyid Vaqar |date=1993 |title=Afghanistan and the Frontier |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c05uAAAAMAAJ |location=[[University of Michigan]] |publisher=Emjay Books International |page=256 |isbn= |editor1-first=Fazal-ur-Rahim Khan |editor1-last=Marwat}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=H Johnson |first1=Thomas |author-link1=Thomas Howard Johnson |last2=Zellen |first2=Barry |date=2014 |title=Culture, Conflict, and Counterinsurgency |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ZZAgAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |page=154 |isbn= 9780804789219}}</ref> and no other group in British India was granted a third option. After the creation of Pakistan in August 1947, Afghanistan  and India financially sponsored the Pashtunistan movement under the leadership of Faqir Ipi.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yca-DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&dq=faqir+of+ipi+pakistan+afghanistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2j7bfx8TZAhVW9mMKHYtuBfoQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=faqir%20of%20ipi%20pakistan%20afghanistan&f=false|title=Soviet-Pakistan Relations and Post-Soviet Dynamics, 1947\u201392|last=Malik|first=Hafeez|date=2016-07-27|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349105731|language=en}}</ref> He continued the guerilla warfare against the new nation\u2019s government.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/77388/the-faqir-of-ipi-of-north-waziristan/ The Faqir of Ipi of North Waziristan]. ''[[The Express Tribune]]''. November 15, 2010.</ref> He didn't surrender to the government of Pakistan and died a natural death in 1960 in Gurwek.<ref name=\"115th anniversary\">[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1086737/april-1891-1960-the-legendary-guerilla-faqir-of-ipi-unremembered-on-his-115th-anniversary/ The legendary guerilla Faqir of Ipi unremembered on his 115th anniversary]. ''The Express Tribune''. April 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMirzali Khan was born in 1897 at Shankai Kirta, a village near Khajuri in the [[Tochi Valley]] of [[North Waziristan]], present day [[Pakistan]] to Sheikh Arsala Khan Wazir.<ref name=\"Alan Warren\">{{cite book|title=Waziristan, the Faqir of Ipi, and the Indian Army: The North West Frontier Revolt of 1936-37|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195790160|page=84|author=Alan Warren}}</ref> He belonged to the Torikhel branch of the [[Utmanzai (Wazir clan)|Utmanzai Wazir]] tribe.<ref name=\"Rob Johnson\">{{cite book|title=The Afghan Way of War: How and Why They Fight|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-979856-8|page=195|author=Rob Johnson}}</ref> His father died when he was twelve. He studied till fourth grade at a government school and later pursued religious studies at [[Bannu]]. He built a mosque and a house at Spalga, further south in North Waziristan agency in 1922. He went to perform [[Hajj]] at [[Mecca]] and later moved to Ipi in mid 1920s. He became a religious figure among the locals and was called \"Haji Sahab\".\n\n== Restoration of King Amanullah Khan ==\nIn 1933, Faqir Ipi went to [[Afghanistan]] to fight against the [[Mohammadzai]] Afghan King at [[Khost]] to support the restoration of King [[Amanullah Khan]]. In 1944, Faqir Ipi joined his fellow [[Loya Paktia]] tribesmen again to support the restoration of Amanullah Khan in the [[Afghan tribal revolts of 1944\u20131947]].<ref name=\"GeorgeHill2013\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TzRlAgAAQBAJ|title=Proceed to Peshawar: The Story of a U.S. Navy Intelligence Mission on the Afghan Border, 1943|last=Hill|first=George|date=2013-11-15|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=|isbn=9781612513287|location=|pages=|quote=Engert letter to State Department, 15 July 1944, says that the rebel leader Abdurrahman, was next in importance to the faqir of Ipi.|language=en|chapter=Chapter 3, the trip (Bibliography near end of the book)}}</ref> Until his death, Faqir Ipi remained involved in Afghan politics as he did not recognize Pakistan.<ref name=\"115th anniversary\">[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1086737/april-1891-1960-the-legendary-guerilla-faqir-of-ipi-unremembered-on-his-115th-anniversary/ The legendary guerilla Faqir of Ipi unremembered on his 115th anniversary]. ''The Express Tribune''. April 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Islam Bibi case ==\nIn March 1936, a British Indian court ruled against the marriage of Islam Bibi (n\u00e9e Ram Kori), a Hindu-converted Muslim girl at [[Jhando Khel]], [[Bannu]], after the girl's family filed case of abduction and forced conversion. The ruling was based on the fact that the girl was a minor and was asked to make her decision of conversion and marriage after she reaches the age of majority, till then she was asked to live with a third party.<ref name=\"Yousef Aboul-Enein\">{{cite book|title=The Secret War for the Middle East|year=2013|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1612513096|page=153|author=Yousef Aboul-Enein|author2=Basil Aboul-Enein}}</ref> The verdict enraged the Pashtuns, and further mobilized Faqir Ipi for a guerrilla war against the British Empire. The [[Dawar (Pashtun tribe)|Dawar]] Maliks and mullahs left the Tochi for the Khaisor Valley to the south to rouse the Torikhel [[Wazir (Pashtun tribe)|Wazirs]]. A month after the incident, Faqir Ipi called a tribal [[jirga]] in the village of Ipi near Mir Ali to declare war against the British imperialists.\n\n== Freedom movement against the British Raj ==\nFaqir's decision to declare war against the British was endorsed by the local Pashtun tribes, who mustered two large lashkars 10,000 strong to battle the British. Interestingly, many Pashtun women also took part in the freedom movement, who not only actively participated in the war but also sung ''landai'' (a short folk-song sung by Pashtun women) to inspire the Pashtun fighters. Widespread lawlessness erupted as the Pashtuns blocked roads, overran outposts and ambushed convoys. In November 1936, the British sent two columns to the Khaisor river valley to crush the freedom movement, but suffered heavy casualties.<ref name=\"at\">{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/__trashed-50/|title=Remembering the Faqir of Ipi|website=Asia Times|date=April 16, 2020|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the Khaisor campaign a general uprising broke out throughout [[Waziristan campaign (1936\u20131939)|Waziristan campaign]], realising the futility of confronting the British Army directly especially with their advantage of air power, tribesmen switched to guerrilla warfare. Squadrons of the two air forces ([[RAF]] and RIAF) tried many tactics including scorched earth retaliation involving the burning of standing crops with jerry can petrol bombs and the killing of cattle with strafing attacks.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nIn 1937, the British sent over 40,000 British-Indian troops, mostly [[Sikhs]] from the [[Punjab]], to crush the freedom movement in Waziristan. This was in response to an ambush by Waziristani tribesmen in which they had killed over 50 British soldiers. However, the British operation failed and by December\u060c the troops were sent back to cantonments. In 1939, the British claimed that the war capacity of Faqir Ipi's forces was enhanced by support from [[Nazi Germany]] and [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Italy]], alleging that the Italian diplomat Pietro Quaroni drove the Italian policy for involvement in Waziristan, although the British could not find any valid evidence for Pietro Quaroni's involvement.<ref name=\"at\"/>\n\nThe British suppressed the agitation by imposing fines and by destroying the houses of their leaders, including that of Faqir Ipi. However, the pyrrhic nature of the victory and the subsequent withdrawal of the troops was credited by the Wazirs to be a manifestation of Faqir Ipi's miraculous powers. He succeeded in inducing a semblance of tribal unity, as the British noticed with dismay, among various sections of Wazirs, Dawar, [[Mahsud]]s and [[Bettani]]s. He cemented his position as religious leader by declaring a Jihad against the British. This move also helped rally support from Pashtun tribesman across the border. In 1946, the British again attempted to crush Faqir Ipi's movement but failed.\n\n==Jirga in Bannu==\nOn 21 June 1947, Faqir Ipi, [[Abdul Ghaffar Khan]], and other [[Khudai Khidmatgar]]s held a jirga in Bannu during which they declared the [[Bannu Resolution]], demanding that the Pashtuns be given a choice to have an independent state of [[Pashtunistan]] composing all Pashtun majority territories of British India, instead of being made to join the new dominions of India or Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|website=The Nation|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> However, the British Raj refused to comply with the demand of the Bannu Resolution and only the options for Pakistan and India were given.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ali Shah |first=Sayyid Vaqar |date=1993 |title=Afghanistan and the Frontier |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c05uAAAAMAAJ |location=[[University of Michigan]] |publisher=Emjay Books International |page=256 |isbn= |editor1-first=Fazal-ur-Rahim Khan |editor1-last=Marwat}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=H Johnson |first1=Thomas |author-link1=Thomas Howard Johnson |last2=Zellen |first2=Barry |date=2014 |title=Culture, Conflict, and Counterinsurgency |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ZZAgAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |page=154 |isbn= 9780804789219}}</ref> In response, Faqir Ipi and the Khudai Khidmatgars boycotted the [[1947 North-West Frontier Province referendum]] on joining India or Pakistan, citing that it did not have the options for the province to become independent or join Afghanistan.\n\n== Pashtunistan movement ==\nFaqir Ipi rejected the creation of Pakistan after the [[partition of India]], considering Pakistan to be a continuation of British imperialism. In 1948, Faqir Ipi took control of North Waziristan's [[Datta Khel Subdivision|Datta Khel]] area and declared the establishment of an independent [[Pashtunistan]], forming ties with regional leaders including [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] and Prince [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]]. On 29 May 1949, Faqir Ipi called a tribal jirga in his headquarters of Gurwek and asked Pakistan to accept Pashtunistan as an independent state. He published a Pashto-language newspaper, ''Gh\u0101z\u012b'', from Gurwek to promote his ideas. In January 1950, a Pashtun [[loya jirga]] in [[Razmak]] symbolically appointed Faqir Ipi as the first president of the \"National Assembly for Pashtunistan\". In 1953-54, the [[Pakistan Air Force]] led an operation from Miramshah airbase and heavily bombarded Faqir Ipi's compound in Gurwek.<ref name=\"at\"/> Although he himself never surrendered to Pakistan until his death in 1960 but his movement diminished after 1954 when his [[Commander-in-chief]] Mehar Dil Khan Mehsud surrendered to the [[Pakistani authorities]] and became loyal to the state of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Aug-2019/past-in-perspective|title=Past in Perspective|date=2019-08-24|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nFaqir Ipi died at night on April 16, 1960. A long term sufferer of asthma during his last days, he became so sick that it was not possible for him to walk for a few steps. People from far away often used to come and see him and ask for his blessing.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} His funeral prayers or Namaz-I-Janaza was held at [[Gurwek]] led by Maulavi Pir Rehman. Thousands of people came for his Namaz-I-Janaza.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} He was buried at Gurwek.\n\n[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Faqir+Aipee+Road,+Islamabad,+Islamabad+Capital+Territory,+Pakistan/@33.648256,73.0152781,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x38df95c0bb738de1:0xf02524d4e38fa35e!8m2!3d33.648256!4d73.0174668 Faqir Aipee Road], a main artery connecting I.J.P. Road to the Kashmir Highway in the federal capital of Pakistan, Islamabad; is named after him.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Waziristan]]\n* [[Mulla Powinda]]\n* [[Sartor Faqir]]\n* [[Umra Khan]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Dr. Shah, Syed Wiqar Ali German Activities in the North-West Frontier Province War Years 1914-1945. Quaid-e-Azam University. Available online at [https://web.archive.org/web/20050120221931/http://www.brain.com.pk/~charsadda/articles/germanarticle.htm]. Last accessed on 22/03/06\n* Government of Pakistan: The Frontier Corps (NWFP) Pakistan and its headquarters. Available online at [https://web.archive.org/web/20060405170741/http://www.pak.gov.pk/public/govt/reports/frontier_corps.htm] Last accessed on 22/03/06\n* Siddiqui A. R. Faqir of Ipi's Cross Border Nexus. Available online [https://web.archive.org/web/20060927155808/http://www.khyber.org/people/sarfaroshan/FaqirofIpisCrossBorderNexus.shtml]. Last accessed on 22/03/06.\n* Hauner, Milan (Jan., 1981) One Man against the Empire: The Faqir of Ipi and the British in Central Asia on the Eve of and during the Second World War. Available online at [http://www.khyber.org/publications/021-025/faqiripi.shtml]. Last accessed on 22/03/06.\n* Shah, Idries, Destination Mecca, Chapter XXIII Contains interview with and the only photograph ever taken of Fakir of Ipi (London 1957). Possibly confirms the Fakir's dervish or Sufi status.\n* Batl-i-Hurriyet: Fakir of Ipi\u2014Iman-Parwar Jihad By Dr Fazal-ur-Rehman Kitab Saraay, First Floor, Alhamd Market, Ghazni Street, Urdu Bazar, Lahore\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Waziristan}}\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/waziristan_and_mughal_empire.shtml Waziristan and Mughal empire]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/nehru_in_waziristan.shtml Nehru in Waziristan]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/images/maps/waziristan.gif Sketch map of Waziristan]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/mehsuds_and_wazirs_the_king-ma.shtml Mehsuds and Wazirs, the King-makers in a game of thrones]\n* [http://www.khyber.org/history/a/lawrence_of_arabia_in_wazirist.shtml Lawrence of Arabia in Waziristan]\n{{Pashtun nationalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faqir Of Ipi}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from North Waziristan]]\n[[Category:Pashtun people]]\n[[Category:Pashtun nationalists]]\n[[Category:Pashtun Sufis]]\n", "name_user": "Saamikhan01", "label": "safe", "comment": "Her name in case is mentioned as Ram Kori", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faqir_Ipi"}
